Brian, All,

There's been discussion about this topic in BT SIG and there's a thought ho=
w to go forward. Please let me know how does it sound for you.

Firstly, the IPSP works so that a 6LN (Node) that wishes to obtain IPv6 con=
nectivity will start advertising it's need. The router (6LBR, center of the=
 star) receives these advertisements and then establishes Bluetooth connect=
ion to said node.

Now, as was said, if the Bluetooth node is using random address, it in rare=
 cases may be in conflict with other nearby nodes, as there's no duplicate =
device address detection procedure in play.

The proposed solution on the table is the following: the router (6LBR) SHAL=
L NOT establish more than one Bluetooth connection for each Bluetooth addre=
ss it sees in use. Hence, after the 6LBR has established a Bluetooth connec=
tion to a node with an address, it will not establish connection to another=
 node that happens to advertise IPv6 support with the same address.  Furthe=
rmore, the node MUST generate its IPv6 Link-Local address based on the devi=
ce address used for establishing Bluetooth connection with the router.

This means that:
-> In the case of conflict only one device of those with conflicting addres=
s gets to join the 6LBR. Other nodes with conflicting address will be left =
stranded, until the moment they change their random device address (action =
that some perform at every boot, some perform periodically, if I understood=
 it right).

-> IPv6 Link-Local address for a node is generated from the Bluetooth addre=
ss used for the Bluetooth connection (and for the duration of the connectio=
n, in case the address is random and changing). Hence the router will know =
what will be, and is, the link-local address of the node it is about to con=
nect.=20

-> As router ensures every Bluetooth node it serves is using different Blue=
tooth address, the 1:1 generated IPv6 Link-Local addresses must then be loc=
ally unique.

With the above, do you agree that we can optimize away joining to solicited=
-node multicast address and avoid performing DAD for the link-local address=
?

When it comes to privacy, the link-local address privacy will go 1:1 with t=
he Bluetooth device address privacy =3D if Bluetooth node uses IEEE 802 add=
ress at Bluetooth level, the corresponding link-local address will be IEEE =
802-based. If Bluetooth node uses random device address, the corresponding =
link-local address will be random as well.

If this approach is acceptable, we'll update the internet-draft accordingly=
.

Best regards,

	Teemu


