Hi Teemu,

On 8/6/14 3:34 AM, teemu.savolainen@nokia.com wrote:
> Brian, All,
>=20
> There's been discussion about this topic in BT SIG and there's a
> thought how to go forward. Please let me know how does it sound for
> you.
>=20
> Firstly, the IPSP works so that a 6LN (Node) that wishes to obtain
> IPv6 connectivity will start advertising it's need. The router (6LBR,
> center of the star) receives these advertisements and then
> establishes Bluetooth connection to said node.
>=20
> Now, as was said, if the Bluetooth node is using random address, it
> in rare cases may be in conflict with other nearby nodes, as there's
> no duplicate device address detection procedure in play.
>=20
> The proposed solution on the table is the following: the router
> (6LBR) SHALL NOT establish more than one Bluetooth connection for
> each Bluetooth address it sees in use. Hence, after the 6LBR has
> established a Bluetooth connection to a node with an address, it will
> not establish connection to another node that happens to advertise
> IPv6 support with the same address.  Furthermore, the node MUST
> generate its IPv6 Link-Local address based on the device address used
> for establishing Bluetooth connection with the router.
>=20
> This means that: -> In the case of conflict only one device of those
> with conflicting address gets to join the 6LBR. Other nodes with
> conflicting address will be left stranded, until the moment they
> change their random device address (action that some perform at every
> boot, some perform periodically, if I understood it right).

In essence, DAD is performed at the BT level.

>=20
> -> IPv6 Link-Local address for a node is generated from the Bluetooth
> address used for the Bluetooth connection (and for the duration of
> the connection, in case the address is random and changing). Hence
> the router will know what will be, and is, the link-local address of
> the node it is about to connect.

It also means that a new BT association (and corresponding IPv6 LL
address) will be needed each time a device changes its BT address.  If
that occurs at random rather than at start up time, a device could lose
connectivity in the middle of application flows.  That is, unless BT
won't allow a new address while data is flowing.

>=20
> -> As router ensures every Bluetooth node it serves is using
> different Bluetooth address, the 1:1 generated IPv6 Link-Local
> addresses must then be locally unique.

Yes.

>=20
> With the above, do you agree that we can optimize away joining to
> solicited-node multicast address and avoid performing DAD for the
> link-local address?

I believe we can avoid DAD in the above scenario.  I would ask that the
document clearly explain the tradeoffs, especially any security issues
that may arise.

>=20
> When it comes to privacy, the link-local address privacy will go 1:1
> with the Bluetooth device address privacy =3D if Bluetooth node uses
> IEEE 802 address at Bluetooth level, the corresponding link-local
> address will be IEEE 802-based. If Bluetooth node uses random device
> address, the corresponding link-local address will be random as
> well.

Yes, and that should be documented as well.

>=20
> If this approach is acceptable, we'll update the internet-draft
> accordingly.

Seems logical to me.

Regards,
Brian



