>allow a new address while data is flowing.

After the Bluetooth LE logical channel between devices has been created, it=
 is referred with Connection Handle (in the HCI interface). Even if a devic=
e changes its random device address used for sending BT advertisements, the=
 logical channel stays in place. Hence 6LN and 6LBR can and should keep usi=
ng the link-local addresses generated from the device addresses used at the=
 time of connection establishment as long as the L2CAP channel stays up.

>> With the above, do you agree that we can optimize away joining to=20
>> solicited-node multicast address and avoid performing DAD for the=20
>> link-local address?
>I believe we can avoid DAD in the above scenario.  I would ask that the do=
cument clearly explain the tradeoffs, especially any security issues that m=
ay arise.

I added some discussion about tradeoffs, but I'm not sure what security new=
 issues might arise from this (except privacy, see below)?

>> When it comes to privacy, the link-local address privacy will go 1:1=20
>> with the Bluetooth device address privacy =3D if Bluetooth node uses=20
>> IEEE 802 address at Bluetooth level, the corresponding link-local=20
>> address will be IEEE 802-based. If Bluetooth node uses random device=20
>> address, the corresponding link-local address will be random as well.
>Yes, and that should be documented as well.

I was planning to add text like this:
---
   The IPv6 link-local address configuration described in Section 3.2.1
   strictly binds the privacy level of IPv6 link-local address to the
   privacy level device has selected for the Bluetooth LE.  This means
   that a device using Bluetooth privacy features will retain the same
   level of privacy with generated IPv6 link-local addresses.
   Respectively, device not using privacy at Bluetooth level will not
   have privacy at IPv6 link-local address either.  For non-link local
   addresses implementations have a choice to support
   [I-D.ietf-6man-default-iids].
---

