Hi Teemu,

On 8/10/14 11:43 AM, teemu.savolainen@nokia.com wrote:
> Hi Brian,
>=20
>>> This means that: -> In the case of conflict only one device of
>>> those with conflicting address gets to join the 6LBR. Other nodes
>>> with conflicting address will be left stranded, until the moment
>>> they change their random device address (action that some perform
>>> at every boot, some perform periodically, if I understood it
>>> right).
>> In essence, DAD is performed at the BT level.
>=20
> Well, perhaps strictly speaking not at the BT level, if you think
> about BT's protocol layers, but rather by support software that
> decides about establishing BT connections. I clarified this to the
> draft.

Ok.

>=20
>>> -> IPv6 Link-Local address for a node is generated from the
>>> Bluetooth address used for the Bluetooth connection (and for the
>>> duration of the connection, in case the address is random and
>>> changing). Hence the router will know what will be, and is, the
>>> link-local address of the node it is about to connect.
>> It also means that a new BT association (and corresponding IPv6 LL=20
>> address) will be needed each time a device changes its BT address.
>>  If that occurs at random rather than at start up time, a device
>> could lose connectivity in the middle of application flows.  That
>> is, unless BT won't allow a new address while data is flowing.
>=20
> After the Bluetooth LE logical channel between devices has been
> created, it is referred with Connection Handle (in the HCI
> interface). Even if a device changes its random device address used
> for sending BT advertisements, the logical channel stays in place.
> Hence 6LN and 6LBR can and should keep using the link-local addresses
> generated from the device addresses used at the time of connection
> establishment as long as the L2CAP channel stays up.

Given that we are talking only about link-local addresses, this seems fin=
e.

>=20
>>> With the above, do you agree that we can optimize away joining to
>>>  solicited-node multicast address and avoid performing DAD for
>>> the link-local address?
>> I believe we can avoid DAD in the above scenario.  I would ask that
>> the document clearly explain the tradeoffs, especially any security
>> issues that may arise.
>=20
> I added some discussion about tradeoffs, but I'm not sure what
> security new issues might arise from this (except privacy, see
> below)?
>=20
>>> When it comes to privacy, the link-local address privacy will go
>>> 1:1 with the Bluetooth device address privacy =3D if Bluetooth node
>>> uses IEEE 802 address at Bluetooth level, the corresponding
>>> link-local address will be IEEE 802-based. If Bluetooth node uses
>>> random device address, the corresponding link-local address will
>>> be random as well.
>> Yes, and that should be documented as well.
>=20
> I was planning to add text like this: --- The IPv6 link-local address
> configuration described in Section 3.2.1 strictly binds the privacy
> level of IPv6 link-local address to the privacy level device has
> selected for the Bluetooth LE.  This means that a device using
> Bluetooth privacy features will retain the same level of privacy with
> generated IPv6 link-local addresses. Respectively, device not using
> privacy at Bluetooth level will not have privacy at IPv6 link-local
> address either.  For non-link local addresses implementations have a
> choice to support [I-D.ietf-6man-default-iids]. ---

Seems reasonable on first read.

Regards,
Brian



