On Thu, Aug 7, 2014 at 9:54 PM, Rene Struik <rstruik.ext@gmail.com> wrote:
> Hi Behcet:
>
> I had a brief look at draft-sarikaya-6lo-cga-nd-00 and have the following
> initial feedback:
>
> 1) While the draft is presented as a lightweight version of SeND (RFC 3971)
> using cryptographically generated addresses [CGA] (RFC 3972), shouldn't one
> consider this as an extension of CGA, where one adds ECC-variants to the
> mix. If so, would it make sense to suggest this draft as an update to those
> RFCs? {This does seem to give your draft wider applicability, also outside
> the LLN realm.}

OK.

> 2) In RFC 6775 (Neighbor Discovery Optimization for IPv6 over Low-Power
> Wireless Personal Area Networks), secure neighbor discovery was considered
> outside scope, although alluded to (at the end of Section 11). I am curious
> as to whether you see cryptographically generated addresses and signatures
> as a viable option here. The main drawbacks I can see are that one cannot
> protect the privacy of signed messages and that the format of CGA itself
> imposes quite a low upper bound on security due to, e.g., impersonation
> attacks (~59 bits with a simple 2nd-preimage attack).

I read Section 11 of RFC 6775 again. My reading is that 6775 mentions
positively of SEND for hosts and router communication.
So I don't see a problem there.

> 3) It may be possible to reduce the size of some of the data formats (e.g.,
> for the digital signature option in Section 4.2 of your draft) somewhat,
> both via cryptographic techniques and by using a more dense lossless
> compression mechanism. This may, e.g., result in being able to squeeze the
> LSEND message in two (rather than three) 802.15.4 frames {bases on
> back-of-the-beer-coaster estimates and your Section 5.1 packet sizes}. I can
> give some more detailed feedback, if I understand somewhat more how you see
> the #2 trade-offs.

Sure, now that we are considering  improvements on the basic LSEND
that I defined such as the one Pascal proposed, I would happy to hear
from you on your proposal.

Regards,

