>>> Le 14 aot 2014  19:44, "Erik Nordmark" <nordmark@acm.org> a crit :
>>>
>>>
>>> I think the WG should collect together requirements for RFC6775bis in a concise form.
>>>
>>> The potential ones I know of are:
>>> - Handling host movement better by being able to determine the most recent ARO
>>> - Working on link-layers and devices that do not use/have EUI-64 identifiers
>>> - Removing the dependency (from the privacy discussion) on having a link-local address which corresponds to the EUI-64
>>> - There are use cases where it it useful to proxy registrations. We probably want to have explicit support for this.
> I have comments on this:
>
>   - Secure? What threats would we be concerned about? Do we need the
> same protections as one would get with SeND? Or would it be sufficient
> to secure the binding between the unique id in the ARO and the host
> which sent it?
>
> I think SeND for RFC 6775 is a very light weight extension and with
> recent suggestions for optimization from Pascal and possibly from
> Rene, it is going to become even more light weight. Why not work on
> it?
>
> So in view of this, I suggest modifying Erik's suggestion as follows:
>
> Support to secure the binding between the unique id in the ARO and the
> host which sent it.

I think that is a reasonable security requirement.

    Erik

>
>
>>> - Handle constrained devices on links that are not necessarily low power? (Currently the assumption is that all the devices on the link are constrained devices that perform ARO).
>>>
>>> Are there other potential requirements?
>>>
>>>    Erik
